ction broadens current critical thinking about Elizabeth, as each of the essays contributes to the debate about the ways in which the queen’s developing iconicity was not simply a celebratory mode, but also encoded criticism of her. Each of these essays explains the ways in which the varied representations of Elizabeth reflect the political and cultural anxieties of her subjects  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aLiterature Studies 2020. 4aShakespeare 2020. 7aLITERARY COLLECTIONS / English, Irish, Scottish, Welsh.2bisacsh  aBritish monarchs.  aElizabethan era.  aJoan of Arc.  aLady Alchymia.  aNew World.  aProphetesse Deborah.  aQueen Elizabeth I.  aVirgin Queen.  aalchemical treatises.  aallegorical personae.  afemale Protestant monarch.  aiconographical repertoire.  aquasi-religious images.  areligious images.1 aArcher, Jayne Elisabeth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBlessing, Carol, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBurgess, Helen J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCampbell, Heather, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aConnolly, Annaliese, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aConnolly, Annaliese, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHopkins, Lisa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHopkins, Lisa, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aNewstok, Scott L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSpiller, Ben, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSteggle, Matthew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWilliams, Deanne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.